Download the file and convert to long format.

time_series_recovered_long <- time_series_recovered %>%

time_series_recovered_long <- time_series_recovered_long %>%

Adaptation of code from Prof. Chris Sutherland Dowload the data

time_series_confirmed_long2 <- read_csv(url("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19/master/csse_covid_19_data/csse_covid_19_time_series/time_series_covid19_confirmed_global.csv")) %>%
  rename(Province_State = "Province/State", Country_Region = "Country/Region") %>%
  pivot_longer(-c(Province_State, Country_Region, Lat, Long),
               names_to = "Date", values_to = "cumulative_cases") %>%
  mutate(Date = mdy(Date) - days(1),
         Place = paste(Lat,Long,sep="_")) %>%
  group_by(Place,Date) %>%
  summarise(cumulative_cases = ifelse(sum(cumulative_cases)>0,
                                      sum(cumulative_cases),NA_real_),
            Lat = mean(Lat),
            Long = mean(Long)) %>%
  mutate(Pandemic_day = as.numeric(Date - min(Date)))
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   .default = col_double(),
##   `Province/State` = col_character(),
##   `Country/Region` = col_character()
## )
## See spec(...) for full column specifications.

Plot the data.

static <- ggplot(subset(time_series_confirmed_long2,Date %in% seq(min(Date),max(Date),14)),
            aes(x = Long, y = Lat, size = cumulative_cases/1000)) +
            borders("world", colour = NA, fill = "grey90") +
            theme_bw() +
            geom_point(shape = 21, color='purple', fill='purple', alpha = 0.5) +
            labs(title = 'COVID-19 spread',x = '', y = '',
                 size="Cases (x1000))") +
            theme(legend.position = "right") +

            facet_wrap(.~Date,ncol=1)

EXERCISES

Graph of COVID Confirmed Cases vs. Recovered in the US. I chose to create this figure because it demonstrates that the number of recovered cases is increasing at the same rate as the number of confirmed cases. If this pattern continues, the rate of recovery will equal, and eventually surpass, the rate of diagnoses.

time_series_long_joined_counts %>% 
  group_by(Country_Region, Report_Type, Date) %>% 
  summarise(Counts = sum(Counts)) %>% 
  filter (Country_Region == "US") %>% 
  filter (Report_Type %in% c("Confirmed", "Recovered")) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Date,  y = log2(Counts), fill = Report_Type, color = Report_Type)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  ggtitle("US COVID-19 Confirmed Cases vs. Recovered")

Graph of COVID Deaths in multiple countries on the same graph. I created this figure to depict how many more deaths the US has than other countries with high confirmed case volumes.

time_series_long_joined %>% 
  group_by(Country_Region,Date) %>% 
  summarise_at(c("Deaths"), sum) %>% 
  filter (Country_Region %in% c("China","France","Italy", 
                                "Korea, South", "US")) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Date,  y = Deaths, color = Country_Region)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  ggtitle("COVID-19 Deaths")

                                "Italy","Spain", "US")) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = Date,  y = Deaths, color = Country_Region)) + 
  geom_point(size = 0.5) +
  geom_line(size = 0.5) +
  ggtitle("Confirmed COVID-19 Deaths") +
  facet_wrap(~Country_Region, ncol=2, scales="fixed") + 
  theme(legend.position = "none")
